Lear discusses his day-to-day affairs including marriage to "my dear Fanny" [Frances Dandridge Henley]; boarding with [Thomas?] Law; 
            initiation in the Masonic Lodge at Alexandria; dining with Jefferson and  Madison, news of the Louisiana Purchase; July 4th celebration; 
            journey to Boston via Baltimore, Philadelphia, and New York; visit to his Portsmouth, N.H. home; a rumor, begun by John Marshall, that he 
            had suppressed certain papers of George Washington; and preparations for the journey to Algiers on the U.S.S. Constitution under Edward P
            reble [no entries the month of the voyage.]
